I see it more clearly in the F
rench field guide by Trape...  its absent in the english guide

@sanghalodge After reviewing your other observations, I think at least three of them are Atheris broadleyi. I'm not so sure about the fourth. And yes, the ranges of both species are very close together where you were.
Thanks, @daniel_liepack, didn't consider this alternative! Could you help me understanding the difference b/w the 2 species?

@daniel_liepack and @viperidae4ever  @riley_frasier  thanks for your id, I assume that the previous Id's of mine of A. squamigera from the same locality are correct? you have both identified these as A squamigera. does this mean we have two species side by side? I have been through my pictures and added a couple more pictures to the previous records as well as a completely new record, I would appreciate your comments.

@jakob The yellowish transverse bands with a black margin across the dorsum and the postocular stripe from the eye to the corner of the mouth are indications for Atheris broadleyi. The area where it was found also points to Atheris broadleyi rather than Atheris squamigera.
